    <h1>&#x2022; Life ex&#xAD;plores fam&#xAD;ily-friendly out&#xAD;ings and stay&#xAD;ca&#xAD;tions</h1>
    <h2>Check out new at&#xAD;trac&#xAD;tions and old favourites with fresh of&#xAD;fer&#xAD;ings</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201122/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-22"><time>2020-11-22</time></a>
        - <span>FRONT PAGE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Ed&#xAD;dino Ab&#xAD;dul Hadi</span>
    </section>

    <p>This year has seen not just the clo­sure of bor­ders, but also the wind­ing down of a pro­fu­sion of pop­u­lar fam­ily haunts such as Kidza­nia, Su­per­park and Cool De Sac.</p>
    <p>But par­ents with young chil­dren look­ing for places to blow off steam dur­ing the school hol­i­days need not fret.</p>
    <p>From in­door play­grounds to an­i­mal-cen­tric at­trac­tions, sev­eral new fam­ily-friendly places have popped up since the start of the year, while old favourites have been spruced up with new of­fer­ings.</p>
    <p>Like many other par­ents with young kids, I am al­ways on the look­out for places where the whole fam­ily can en­joy new ex­pe­ri­ences.</p>
    <p>To­gether with my wife and our daugh­ters, aged seven and 22 months, I check out seven new at­trac­tions that were launched, or re­launched, in re­cent months.</p>
    <p>Here are the low­down and high­lights.</p>

